snippet.title: 5 Best Croissants in Paris RANKED - French Friday - Great Croissants in Paris
snippet.description:
Links to the 5 Best Croissants in Paris below! Find even more amazing croissants in Paris with my guide here http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide or on an interactive map with all the croissant locations plus way more by becoming a Patron (read this: https://www.patreon.com/posts/announcing-map-19887642) via Mapstr. Then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson (me) http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (merch - Sonja Bajic's the guest illustrator too!)
http://bit.ly/JaySwansonBooks (my books)
http://bit.ly/CameraFour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Music by: Dyalla

Sonja's map of the Five Best* Croissants in Paris! http://instagram.com/sonjabajic

The 5 Best* Croissants in Paris:
1) Gontran Cherrier: https://goo.gl/maps/j1sgEH6jrTx
2) Boulangerie Terroir d’Avenir: https://goo.gl/maps/j8iu6Xn98Lz
3) Eric Kaser: https://goo.gl/maps/NCewriNfHdA2
4) Laurent Duchêne: https://goo.gl/maps/BBLNq6qN14s
5) Des Gâteaux et du Pain: https://goo.gl/maps/9ZWjT1bVEvA2

^I mean, they're great. I wouldn't know for sure that they're the BEST because I haven't yet tried ALL the croissants in Paris. But they are delicious.

For more coffee and croissants in Paris style recommendations, be sure to stick around - plenty more to come!

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I currently film almost exclusively with my Samsung Galaxy S8: http://amzn.to/2lPKSpZ

How do you get those shots where you're walking or running? - A Joby Gorillapod for smartphones, like this: http://amzn.to/2sXNIL3

You drop your phone a lot, how does it survive? - THIS CASE IS AMAZING: http://amzn.to/2hoxgTA (Galaxy S7) - http://amzn.to/2Dt08Bu (Galaxy S8) - http://amzn.to/2FxVliP (iPhone)

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

But what are you doing there? - Living it up! https://youtu.be/ZW2RP--DO8Y

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - what's your PayPal? - Here's a handy link! https://www.paypal.me/jayswanson

I like PayPal in pink! - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French one: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Can I come stay with you in Paris? - Have you seen my apartment? It's too small for me as it is! https://youtu.be/6t2qj3rdyX8

OK, but how do I use the Metro when I'm there? - I made a handy video for you: https://youtu.be/T0YS5si8bJs

replies.textDisplay:
Jay Swanson ah i see, i’m going to Paris from Berlin on Monday, and looking for a one day trip around Paris. Is it better to use metro to go around or hop on hop off? I’ve never been to Paris before, and i only have 8hours to explore Paris before going back to Berlin for a meeting. My flight is at 22.30 at Charles De Gaulle, what time should i depart from Paris? (I’m gonna use the Metro to go to the airport)
Please help........
replies.textOriginal:
Jay Swanson ah i see, i’m going to Paris from Berlin on Monday, and looking for a one day trip around Paris. Is it better to use metro to go around or hop on hop off? I’ve never been to Paris before, and i only have 8hours to explore Paris before going back to Berlin for a meeting. My flight is at 22.30 at Charles De Gaulle, what time should i depart from Paris? (I’m gonna use the Metro to go to the airport)
Please help........

replies.textDisplay: You can get passes at the windows in the larger metro stations - but if you aren't going to be in Paris for long, or are getting in late in the month or the middle of the week, it becomes much less worthwhile. 1-3 day passes are often ideal in that case, if you'll use the metro a ton. Have a great trip! =D

comments.textDisplay:
I like Eric Kayser but Du Pain et des Idées is the one I really want to try. Christophe Vassueur makes everything by hand. He only does viennoiserie. This is what Paris use to be like. You either did viennoiserie or pastries. The belief was that you could only do one well and the other would be so so.
I want to try Blé Sucré. Their croissants are supposed to be really good. The other item I want to try is their Madeleines. They are supposed to be the best.

I do a bit of baking and have made croissants a few times and it's not hard just time consuming. I pay $3 for a butter croissant and $4 for an almond croissant here at home. We have a french Pastry café and Franck is a baker by trade. His almond croissant it the best I've ever had.
I love Madeleines as well. I'm not a huge fan of frosting so a bit size cake with no frosting is wonderful too me. So, if you checkout Blé Sucré get a Madeleine or two.
